      "block_id": "3354750c-f3ba-8056-a263-d46ac4f871d1",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Moment of Prediction",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Course Success",
          "Final course grade above class median vs below class median",
          "2093 students",
          "10 fully online introductory STEM courses at a large public U.S. university",
          "SIS data, LMS logs, Survey Data",
          "[female, transfer, low income, first-generation, URM, SAT total score, high school GPA, total clicks and total time in the first half of the course, plus category-specific clicks/time (portal, tasks, content, communication, performance, miscellaneous), effort regulation, time management, environment management, self-efficacy]",
          "First half of course / first 5 weeks",
          "Students with missing values on more than 25% of features were dropped. Continuous numerical variables were standardized by centering to the median and scaling by the IQR. Remaining missing values were handled with multivariate imputation. Click features were restricted to the first half of the course to support early identification.",
          "Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest",
          "Course-level leave-one-group-out cross-validation across the 10 courses",
          "{Accuracy: 0.675 – Institutional + Click + Survey}",
          "Institutional and LMS data both had useful predictive value, and combining them improved performance. Survey data alone had weak predictive utility. In fairness terms, institutional data tended to underpredict historically disadvantaged students, while LMS data sometimes overpredicted some groups.\n\n\n\n",
          "Only 10 online STEM courses at one institution. Click features were deliberately coarse and not course-specific. Survey features covered only a limited set of self-regulated learning constructs. The study evaluates fairness but does not test bias-mitigation strategies.\n\n\n"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Long-term college success",
          "Average GPA in the following academic year above class median vs below class median",
          "2093 students",
          "10 fully online introductory STEM courses at a large public U.S. university",
          "SIS data, LMS logs, Survey Data",
          "[female, transfer, low income, first-generation, URM, SAT total score, high school GPA, total clicks and total time in the first half of the course, plus category-specific clicks/time (portal, tasks, content, communication, performance, miscellaneous), effort regulation, time management, environment management, self-efficacy]",
          "First half of course, predicting following-year GPA",
          "Students with missing values on more than 25% of features were dropped. Continuous numerical variables were standardized by centering to the median and scaling by the IQR. Remaining missing values were handled with multivariate imputation. Click features were computed from the first half of the course, while the target was long-term GPA in the following academic year.",
          "Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest",
          "Course-level leave-one-group-out cross-validation across the 10 courses. For each feature-set/outcome combination, the classifier with the highest F-score was retained. Evaluation considered Accuracy, FPR, and FNR, with subgroup fairness analysis via disparity ratios and one-sided two-proportion z-tests.",
          "{Accuracy: 0.650 – Institutional + Click}",
          "LMS and institutional data both predicted long-term success reasonably well, and their combination performed best. Survey data again showed limited added value. Fairness analysis showed persistent underestimation of disadvantaged groups when institutional data were used, and combining data sources did not fully remove bias.",
          "Only 10 online STEM courses at one institution. Long-term success is operationalized relative to classmates via median split rather than raw GPA. Fairness was analyzed at the data-source level, but no debiasing intervention was tested."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
